content.description: A new classic at Rattlesnake. Starts with an easy bouldering crack and leads  to small, widely spaced holds. Finishes with shoe smears and a small right hand finger crack.
content.protection: Top rope or a 30 foot boulder problem!
content.location: This is the nose to the left of Timber Rattler on the Upper Tier. See photos for details.

content.description: Excellent dihedral climbing with a finger crack.
content.protection: Small cams or large pad.
content.location: Obvious 20ft dihedral on the upper tier of the main bluff. Directly above Fists and Fury.

content.description: Excellent short route accented with a mix of short pulls,lay backs, balancing, and cracks.  Would be a great second pitch to Solo, Anniversary, Black Hornet, or Slab Cracks. Named for the timber rattlesnake found in the area and the dead pine felled off route face. TIMMMMMBERRRR!
content.protection: Easy top rope access/set-up. Bring a set of wired nuts, small/med cams. First pro placement is at about 20 ft.
content.location: Located above Solo Crack on upper tier.  Left towering buttress.

content.description: Starts with good holds and move up to a large blank section. The right arete will help here. Strong and burely. Holds can be seen, but havent figured out how to get them or use them.
content.protection: pads and spotters
content.location: arete right of Criminal Mastermind

content.description: Start as for Speechless, on the left side of the arete, with an undercling for the left hand and the arete for the right.  Climb the left side of the arete.  For the record, Speechless moves right around the arete about half way up.
content.protection: Pads.  Flat landing though it is possible the wall behind could come into play..
content.location: On the main formation just right of the saddle you reach between the hills when walking from the car.

content.description: Nice crack line with many stances and pro.
content.protection: Medium cams.
content.location: West side of main bluff, first good crack pm the left. There's a small stump at about 5ft.

content.description: Overhanging finger crack leading to a loose chock stone, finishing on nice holds, leading to the bus stop on top. I used the left corner arete to aid in the climb. Turkey vultures like to perch on top in the warm fall sun.
content.protection: Top rope is an easy set-up. Crack will take mixed sizes of wired nuts and small cams.  Once at the loose chock stone the route can be run out.  Bottom 15 feet is the climb.
content.location: Around right corner from Timber Rattler on upper tier, left buttress.

content.description: Route starts by mounting the overhang and clambering to the ledge as in Massasauga.  Step to the right above the long overhang and mount the exposed wall and climb nose to the top.
content.protection: Recommend top rope......bottom crack/overhang is too big for gear and top is small ledge holds.....or a stunt man air bag and a long boulder problem.
content.location: Located to right of Massasauga on Upper Tier at top of gully wash entrance.....South end of main cliff and up top.

content.description: Short crack to the right and in the corner from Snakes on a Plain. Short jam crack with some overhang angle in the middle.
content.protection: Mixed cams, med/large hexes, top rope.
content.location: Upper tier on the left buttress around the right corner from Timber Rattler and in the corner right of Snakes on a Plain.  See photos for route.

content.description: Nice balance climb on thin holds leading to lay-backs on big sloper jugs; up the left arete face and stepping across to finish the blocky top face.
content.protection: Top rope set up is easy; not sure with trad other than really thin gear.
content.location: Left of Upper Tier Dihedral on left side of face.  Starts on the diagonal crack. See photo outlying the route.

content.description: Excellent hand jams lead to a sloping top-out on jugs.
content.protection: Medium cams.
content.location: Crack left of Fists and Fury that ends on slab directly left of big boulder sitting on top.

content.description: Upper tier chimney climb with three inner cracks. Great beginner lead climb.
content.protection: Bring all you got.....For beginners, you will be able to use cams, hexes, nuts, and can gain experience in stemming, jams, and chimney techniques. Short and sweet.
content.location: Located in the upper tier to the left of Massasuaga; where the gully wash access tops out.

content.description: Tricky, sandy, sloper climbing. Tricky at the top.
content.protection: TR, no gear on route. There is a nice tree for an anchor at the top.
content.location: West side of main bluff, just right of Chossholic.

content.description: Great crack climbing with an exposed top section.  Climb starts with an off-width crack leading to a shelf.  Step across to the mid-section on smaller finger cracks and limited foot holds. Make the reach to the bucket hold and finish on the top latticed face. Step up onto the final boulder and shout "MASSASAUGA"!
content.protection: Great trad climb with med/large cams, larger hexes, and nuts on top section. Can be top-roped also.
content.location: Located on upper tier, at the top and right of the gully-wash access.

content.description:
Start with your left hand on the clean arete, and right with a low, obvious undercling.  The opening move is the distinct crux.  Climb the striking arete, finishing on an obvious ledge. 

If you jump start the first move it is a fun 4/5.

 A groove chimney left is not a bad way to downclimb.
content.protection: Pads and spot.  4 pads probably, there is a slight downward slant in the landing that should be leveled.
content.location: Walk up the trail from the parking.  At the obvious saddle between the hills this is on the formation to the right just uphill.  The chaos/ hocus pocus wall is just 50 feet away on the backside of the main formation.  Speechless finishes on this climb, though starts on the other side of the arete.

content.description: Old school cool fist crack. Solo up easy terrain then plug bomber cams in a hand crack. The crack gets wider and harder as you go up. Fists to arm-bar.
content.protection: #4 C4 for the crux, maybe a #5.
content.location: West side of the main bluff. It sits directly underneath a large boulder on the top.

content.description: Between two bluffs in saddle look for vertical boulder with easy climbing.  Good warm up.
content.protection: Pads
content.location: Between two bluffs in the saddle.  Look south when crossing saddle and you will see the arete.

content.description: Interesting tight dihedral climbing.
content.protection: Pads
content.location: On the north side of the main bluff. Dihedral between Criminal Mastermind and Speechless.

content.description: Sit start on large holds. Move up to thin sidepull, get your feet up and huck for another large hold, move up and grab arete on right, gain crimp or sidepull and make large move to top.
content.protection: pads and spotters. The landing is ok until you get up about halfway. If you dryfired from there, you'd probably miss the pads and fly down the talus.
content.location: about 30 feet above Easy Arete.

content.description: Chossy crack climb. I went to OS this one day but bailed when the choss started to consume me.
content.protection: TR or deep gear in shitty rock.
content.location: Crack system right of Fists and Fury.

content.description: Sit start with left hand in a two finger pocket and right on a sharp edge. Follow left hand side pulls and right hand jugs to the top.
content.protection: pad and spotter
content.location: Below the speechless area.

content.description: This route coined the name from a hornets nest that had to be removed half way up (half way down on rappel), and from the remains of the black charred tree trunk at the start of the climb. This is a fun zig-zag crack with lay-backs and jamming. The last ten feet are slightly overhung and finishes on good hand holds.
content.protection: Route will take everything from cams, hexes, nuts and of course a top rope set-up.
content.location: Route is directly between Anniversary and Slab Crack.

content.description: Half crack leading to a challenging crux move to gain the horizontal ledge for foot placement. Continue up and left on sloped friction ledges to gain final finish straight up nice spaced hand and foot placements.  I solo'ed this on a petzl shunt and top roped it five days later with a friend.  The name derives from my ascent on my parents 58th wedding anniversary on August 24th.
content.protection: On top rope I used a #2 and #3 Camelot on the large boulder on top and a long webbing to a small but secure pine tree. Route will take pro but remember this is soft/chossy sandstone.
content.location: Route is next half-crack to the right of Solo Crack (5.4). See photo for route. Area between red marks is the crux. Route finishes where boulder is resting on top.

content.description: This is the west side of the main cliff. It has a lower and upper tier. There are some cool routes mixed in with boulder problems.
